<section class="chapter chapter--dark" id="chapter-stats" data-chapter="Why It Matters">
  <div class="chapter__inner">
    <div class="chapter__content chapter__content--center reveal">
      <span class="eyebrow">The Pattern</span>
      <h2 class="headline-chapter">Where These Claims Come From</h2>
      <p class="subheadline">
        The "Lost Cause" narrative was deliberately constructed after the war to reframe
        the Confederacy's defeat. These talking points have a documented history stretching
        back over a century.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="chapter__content chapter__content--wide">
      <div class="myth-origin-grid reveal">
        <article class="myth-origin-card">
          <span class="myth-origin-card__date">1866-1920</span>
          <h3 class="myth-origin-card__title">The Lost Cause</h3>
          <p class="myth-origin-card__text">
            Confederate veterans' groups and sympathetic historians reframed the war as a noble
            struggle for "states' rights" and Southern honor, deliberately minimizing slavery's role.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="myth-origin-card">
          <span class="myth-origin-card__date">1890s-1960s</span>
          <h3 class="myth-origin-card__title">Textbook Campaigns</h3>
          <p class="myth-origin-card__text">
            The United Daughters of the Confederacy successfully lobbied to change school
            textbooks across the South, embedding Lost Cause narratives in public education.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="myth-origin-card">
          <span class="myth-origin-card__date">1948-Present</span>
          <h3 class="myth-origin-card__title">Political Revival</h3>
          <p class="myth-origin-card__text">
            Confederate symbols resurged during the civil rights era as explicit opposition
            to desegregation, later defended with "heritage" arguments.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

